SIMPLE: infect
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infect
<hw>In*fect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>infectus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>infect</ets>. See <er>Infect</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Infected. Cf. <er>Enfect</er>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infect
<hw>In*fect"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Infected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Infecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>infectus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>inficere</ets> to put or dip into, to stain, infect; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>facere</ets> to make; cf. F.
<ets>infecter</ets>. See <er>Fact</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To taint with morbid matter or any pestilential or
noxious substance or effluvium by which disease is produced; <as>as, to
<ex>infect</ex> a lancet; to <ex>infect</ex> an
apartment.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To affect with infectious disease; to communicate
infection to; <as>as, <ex>infected</ex> with the plague</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Them that were left alive being <qex>infected</qex> with this
disease.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. North.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To communicate to or affect with, as qualities or
emotions, esp. bad qualities; to corrupt; to contaminate; to taint by
the communication of anything noxious or pernicious.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Infected</qex> Ston's daughters with like heat.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To contaminate with illegality or
to expose to penalty.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To poison; vitiate; pollute; defile.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infecter</ent>⟦br⟧
